  "prompt": "The bond angle of Sulphur dioxide is greater than that of Ozone. Why?",
  "response": "To understand why the bond angle of sulfur dioxide (SO\u2082) is greater than that of ozone (O\u2083), we need to consider the molecular geometry and the electronic structure of each molecule.\n\n1. **Molecular Geometry and Bond Angle:**\n   - **Sulfur Dioxide (SO\u2082):** SO\u2082 has a bent molecular geometry. The central sulfur atom is surrounded by two oxygen atoms and has one lone pair of electrons. The bond angle in SO\u2082 is approximately 120\u00b0.\n   - **Ozone (O\u2083):** Ozone also has a bent molecular geometry. The central oxygen atom is surrounded by two other oxygen atoms and has one lone pair of electrons. The bond angle in O\u2083 is approximately 117\u00b0.\n\n2. **Electronic Structure and Bonding:**\n   - **Sulfur Dioxide (SO\u2082):** The sulfur atom in SO\u2082 has a larger atomic size than oxygen. Sulfur can accommodate a larger electron cloud, and the double bonds between sulfur and oxygen have more p\u03c0-d\u03c0 bonding character due to the availability of d-orbitals in sulfur. This results in less repulsion between the bonding pairs, leading to a larger bond angle.\n   - **Ozone (O\u2083):** In ozone, the central oxygen atom forms a coordinate covalent bond with one of the terminal oxygen atoms. The bond order is 1.5 (resonance between two structures), and the bonding involves p\u03c0-p\u03c0 overlap. The smaller size of oxygen atoms leads to more electron-electron repulsion, causing a smaller bond angle.\n\n3. **Lone Pair Repulsion:**\n   - Both molecules have one lone pair on the central atom, which contributes to the bent geometry. However, the larger size of the sulfur atom in SO\u2082 reduces the lone pair-bond pair repulsion effect compared to the smaller oxygen atom in O\u2083.\n\nIn summary, the bond angle of sulfur dioxide is greater than that of ozone primarily due to the larger size of the sulfur atom, the nature of the bonding (p\u03c0-d\u03c0 in SO\u2082 vs. p\u03c0-p\u03c0 in O\u2083), and the reduced lone pair repulsion effect in SO\u2082. These factors collectively result in a larger bond angle for SO\u2082 compared to O\u2083.",
